\series bold 
Theory of 2D Momentum Conservation 
\layout Standard

Since momentum is a vector, the Law of Conservation of Momentum in two dimension
s requires that if the vector conservation equation is broken into components
 then the conservation law must also hold for each of the vector components.
 Thus, if we consider the interaction of several objects, and if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma \overrightarrow{p}=\overrightarrow{p_{1i}}+\overrightarrow{p_{2i}}+\overrightarrow{p_{3i}}+\ldots =\overrightarrow{p_{1f}}+\overrightarrow{p_{2f}}+\overrightarrow{p_{3f}}+\ldots =a\: constant\]

\end_inset 

then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma p_{x}=p_{1ix}+p_{2ix}+p_{3ix}+\ldots =p_{1fx}+p_{2fx}+p_{3fx}+\ldots =a\: constant\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Sigma p_{y}=p_{1iy}+p_{2iy}+p_{3iy}+\ldots =p_{1fy}+p_{2fy}+p_{3fy}+\ldots =a\: constant\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

If a coordinate system is chosen and a given momentum vector makes an angle
 
\begin_inset Formula \( \theta  \)
\end_inset 

 with respect to the designated x-axis then the momentum vector can be broken
 into components in the usual way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overrightarrow{p}=p_{x}\widehat{i}+p_{y}\widehat{j}=p\cos \theta \widehat{i}+p\sin \theta \widehat{j}\]

\end_inset 


